<p>Because of my strong academic performance, I was selected as a teaching assistant for algorithm design course. In that role, one accomplishment I am very proud of was starting my personal website, where I posted study notes to help my classmates and answered their questions in labs. I also built a strong relationship with my professor Jason, and as a result, I took my dissertation project directly from him.</p>
<p>For that project, I developed an algorithm visualizer in JavaScript and React that captures algorithm execution states and turns them into smooth animations with colour feedback and playback controls. I really enjoyed this work because I was able to leverage my solid cs knowledge to engineer a full-stack software product, involving every stage of a SDLC.</p>
<p>After that, I decided to pursue my master’s degree in Advanced Computing at King’s College London because I became more interested in how systems work under the hood. For example, I built a WHILE language compiler in Java and Scala, covering lexing, parsing, and JVM bytecode generation. In the era of AI, English is the new programming language as we move up to another abstraction level, but I believe my ability to dive into the 0s and 1s gives me confidence to solve difficult challenges, rather than just relying on high-level tools.</p>
<p>I have also gained internship experience at Bright Network and Amazon, where I developed an A* pathfinding solution for their self-driving factory vehicles. I was able to reduce unnecessary node exploration and improve routing efficiency under real-world constraints.</p>
<p>I understand that for this role, you are looking for someone with... Overall, due to my strong academic background, my experience in full-stack, system-level projects, and my passion in software development, I am more than prepared to harness my full potential to succeed in your team.</p>
<h2 id="why-do-you-want-to-work-in-this-company-motivation" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#why-do-you-want-to-work-in-this-company-motivation"><span>Why Do You Want to Work in This Company? (Motivation)</span></a></h2>
<h3 id="alternatives-1" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#alternatives-1"><span>Alternatives</span></a></h3>
<ul>
<li>&quot;Why Should We Hire You?&quot;</li>
<li>“Why do you want this job?”</li>
<li>“Why are you the right person for this job?”</li>
<li>“What sets you apart from other candidates?”</li>
<li>“What makes you a good fit for the role?”</li>
<li>“Why do you think you can do well in this job?”</li>
<li>“What can you bring to the company?”</li>
<li>“Why is our company interesting to you?”</li>
<li>“What do you know about our industry?”</li>
<li>“What can you offer us that someone else can not?</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="why-they-ask-1" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#why-they-ask-1"><span>Why They Ask?</span></a></h3>
<ul>
<li>Identifies multiple motivational interests</li>
<li>Evidence of candidate research demonstrated by utilising examples specific to the organisation/ opportunity</li>
<li>Clear evidence of how candidate’s knowledge, experience, strengths and skills will benefit the organisation</li>
<li>Demonstrates long-term commitment and career goals consistent with the opportunity.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="strategy-1" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#strategy-1"><span>Strategy</span></a></h3>
<p>The Circle of Motivation or '<strong>3Rs</strong>'. (Reasoning -&gt; Research -&gt; Relevance -&gt; Reasoning)</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Reasoning</strong></li>
</ol>
<p>The 1st layer represents a key 'pillar' of the motivational argument. This could be anything from particular aspects of the role, the nature of the product or service offered, the culture, training and development opportunities to types of client or customers to be engaged with.</p>
<p>In reality, many candidates may offer quite similar reasons for their interest. The key is what happens next.......</p>
<ol start="2">
<li><strong>Research</strong></li>
</ol>
<p>The 2nd layer allows you to begin to differentiate your argument by using SPECIFIC evidence drawn from the research you've undertaken into the organisation/ role opportunity.</p>
<p>Citing these types of specific researched examples for each of your core reasons allows you to pass the recruiter's 'blind test' - i.e. the researched examples are only applicable to this particular opportunity/ employer.</p>
<ol start="3">
<li><strong>Relevance</strong></li>
</ol>
<p>The final layer is often that omitted by most candidates but in reality is the most important - why does the reasoning matter to you and how can you prove it?</p>
<p>Ideally, this would be by using a specific personal example by way of illustration.</p>
<h3 id="tips-1" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#tips-1"><span>Tips</span></a></h3>
<ul>
<li>3 is the magic number: within a typical 2 minute answer, the Circle of Motivation can be used to give multiple strands of reasoning within the same answer - as a guide, 3 strands is ideal.</li>
<li>Make it personal: when conducting research into the role/ employer, look for examples that relate back to you in terms of academic subjects, projects, work experience, recent news items or anything else that helps provide evidence of a genuine interest.</li>
<li>The recruiter will generally be far more interested in why you're the right candidate for them. If this happens to coincide with how this opportunity is right for you, well then that’s all well and good.</li>
</ul>
