<h2 id="what-is-leadership" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#what-is-leadership"><span>What is Leadership?</span></a></h2>
<p>How to define a good leader? First, he must have willingness to accomplish something that can make the world a better place. Then, he must have wisdom to find people who shares the same value instead of being a lone wolf. He must also have the power to unite those people together to make contribution instead of abusing the power. Finally, he must have vision to assign his successors that carry on the culture to either finish the unfinishing work or expand the flourishment.</p>
<h2 id="how-do-you-use-ai-today-and-what-role-does-it-play-in-how-you-work" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#how-do-you-use-ai-today-and-what-role-does-it-play-in-how-you-work"><span>How do you use AI today, and what role does it play in how you work?</span></a></h2>
<p>I use AI as a daily thinking partner, not as a replacement for my own judgement. It helps me learn faster, work more efficiently, and stay organised in daily life.</p>
<p>For daily learning, I use AI to explain difficult technical concepts in simpler language, especially when I am studying advanced topics like algorithms, operating systems, distributed systems, or system design. For example, when I am learning a new concept, I might first ask AI for an intuitive explanation, then ask for examples, edge cases, and practical usage. I also use it to review my own understanding by asking it to challenge my assumptions or quiz me. This makes my learning more active rather than just reading passively.</p>
<p>For working and software development, AI plays the role of a productivity assistant. I use it to brainstorm implementation approaches, compare trade-offs, debug issues, write cleaner documentation, and review code for readability or edge cases. For example, I am currently working on a small operating system project, I may ask AI to help me think through API design, error handling, database structure, or testing strategy. However, I always treat AI suggestions critically. I still read the code, verify the logic, run tests, and make the final decisions myself, because AI can be wrong or miss context, plus I believe the best way of learning is doing, especially at the early stage of my career.</p>
<p>For daily life, I use AI to organise my thoughts and communicate more clearly. For example, I use it to polish emails, plan tasks, and break down complex goals into manageable steps. As a non-native English speaker, AI is also very useful for improving the naturalness and clarity of my English, especially in professional communication.</p>
<p>Overall, AI helps me reduce repetitive work, learn more independently, and communicate more effectively. The biggest value is that it gives me faster feedback and more perspectives, but I see it as a tool that supports my thinking rather than replaces it. I still need to bring the domain knowledge, critical thinking, and responsibility for the final outcome.</p>
